ional calculation of the costs and benefits of working within formal and informal labor markets to secure household power. She posits that increasing adherence to Islam and taking up the veil on the part of women has been partially motivated by women's desire to protect and promote their interests both within and beyond households.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHome economicszEgyptxCairo Region. 0aHome economicszEgyptzCairo Region. 0aHouseholdsxEconomic aspectszEgyptxCairo Region. 0aHouseholdsxEconomic aspectszEgyptzCairo Region. 0aPoorzEgyptxCairo Region. 0aPoorzEgyptzCairo Region. 0aSex rolezEgyptxCairo Region. 0aSex rolezEgyptzCairo Region. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aarab muslim families.  aarab.  aarranged marriages.  acairo.  aconservatism.  aconsumption.  acultural studies.  aeconomic liberalization policy.  aegypt.  aemployment.  aethnography.  afamily.  aformal labor markets.  agender studies.  ahousehold economy.  ahousehold power.  ainformal labor markets.  ainternational migration.  aislam.  alabor market.  alove marriages.  amarital conflicts.  amarriage negotiations.  amarriage.  amodern economy.  amoney management.  amuslim.  asexual politics.  asocial networks.  asuitor.  asurvival strategies.  atraditional muslim women.  awearing a veil.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052020825440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520918863?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520918863423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520918863/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEB